post_text:
Special board meeting September 10

Dear Parents and Guardians,

On Thursday, Sept. 10, the SCASD Board of Directors will hold a special online meeting at 7 p.m. to discuss updating the district’s health and safety plan and adopting guidelines for reopening our schools.

Watch the district website for registration information (https://www.scasd.org/Page/38075), and the meeting will be broadcast on Channel 98 and streamed live on YouTube.

As a reminder, for the time being, we will decide on our weekly status every Friday after reviewing local COVID-19 data.

Sincerely,

Bob O’Donnell
Superintendent of Schools

post_text:
Dear Parents and Guardians,

Last night, our Board of Directors voted to not have school on Friday, Sept. 4. This applies to all students: in-school, remote and Virtual Academy. This is not a switch to full remote learning; it’s akin to a snow day for students with no instruction, and will be made up on Dec. 23. Because of the rising number of COVID-19 cases reported in our county yesterday, the Board took action to use Friday to further assess the local data we are receiving and better inform our course of action.

Right now, no decisions have been made regarding next week. Over the next couple of days, we will continue to evaluate COVID-19 cases in our community and let you know once we make a decision regarding Tuesday.

If in schools Tuesday, it will be an A-L day for secondary. Middle school Cycle day 3. Elementary Cycle Day 3.

Sincerely,

Bob O’Donnell
Superintendent of Schools

We have had many members of the SCASD community reaching out asking about ways that they can help support SCASD students and families in need. We greatly appreciate the generosity of our community and want to share some ways that you can help.

Right now, we are looking for volunteers to help with transporting SCASD lunches and food bank deliveries, supplies, and of course, monetary donations are always appreciated. If you are interested in helping, please fill out the Community Support & Donations Volunteer form: https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSdWDJ_pWyiT7BEec6_fzlJAKICA6xpyHWAsBJZte77ozaHSpA/viewform?usp=sf_link.

Thank you for your consideration and please feel free to share this form as you see fit. If you have questions or suggestions, please reach out to the Social Work Team at studentservices@scasd.org.

post_text: SCASD Food Services, along with a host of volunteers, continue to serve thousands of meals every Wednesday. Thank you!
shared_text:
SCASD Food Services
July 15 at 8:53 PM ·

SCASD Food Service Department staff and volunteers handed out 1,308 meal kits - each containing food for 5 breakfasts and 5 lunches - to community families today. That brings our grand total since March to 199,814 meals to make life just a little bit easier during this crazy time. Thanks so much to the wonderful families who come to pick up and share their love and joy with us and let us know that our work is appreciated! Any family can order meals for children age 18 and younger at www.scasd.org/freemeals. Pick up is on Wednesdays from 10:00 until 1:00.

post_text:
Our district is currently seeking community members to serve on our CAC for Technology.

The Citizens Advisory Committee (CAC) for Technology was established to advise the Board on matters related to Information Technology including the appropriate use of technology for instructional and administrative purposes. The CAC for Technology is a standing and continuing advisory group to the Board. The CAC for Technology will meet at least quarterly. The CAC for Technology may receive specific requests from the Board for study. Such requests will be made in form of a memo to the chair of the CAC for Technology.

The Board will select at least seven (7) citizens and two (2) SCASD employees to serve on the CAC for Technology. Those members will select a chair from among their members. A liaison from the Board and the SCASD Director of Technology will serve in an advisory capacity to the CAC for Technology.

Read more and apply here: https://www.scasd.org/Page/33504

post_text: Welcome to the State College Area School District’s Virtual Music Showcase. Over the last several weeks, we have gathered performances from some of the most talented musicians throughout our district and pieced them together into one incredible show. Our presentation features 70 acts with over 100 performers. The musicians highlighted are our students, faculty and staff members, as well as some surprise guests representing every school in the district. Please join us Friday, June 5 at 7 p.m. for the premiere!

post_text:
In the midst of finishing this school year, we’re busy planning for the 2020-2021 year. We understand that the community has many questions about what the fall will look like for our district, and to provide as many answers as we can at this point, we have prepared this video presentation.

Our goals with this presentation are to inform you about our planning to date, explain our direction, and respond to your inquiries. This includes information about how we will return to schools as well as our plan for remote learning.

In the video, Superintendent Bob O'Donnell is joined by Finance and Operations Officer Randy Brown and Director of Student Services Jeanne Knouse. As part of our presentation, we provide details about the district teams that are developing protocols for three key areas: health and wellness, educational model and operations.

Local Power Outages and Internet Disruptions

Today, we are experiencing power outages and Internet disruptions throughout the district due to inclement weather. Because of this, it might not be possible for some students and teachers to communicate effectively.

If you experience a disruption, please do not worry. Once this passes, please contact your child’s teachers with any questions. Any teachers who were impacted will notify students with any changes.
text:
Local Power Outages and Internet Disruptions

Today, we are experiencing power outages and Internet disruptions throughout the district due to inclement weather. Because of this, it might not be possible for some students and teachers to communicate effectively.

If you experience a disruption, please do not worry. Once this passes, please contact your child’s teachers with any questions. Any teachers who were impacted will notify students with any changes.

post_text:
Thank you, Megan Schaper, our Food Services Director, for all the work you are doing to feed children during our COVID-19 shutdown and congratulations for being recognized as one of the essential workers heroes. Megan and her team of staff and volunteers are doing an incredible job.

Here is what her colleague Travis Folmar said about her, "State College School District Food Service Director Megan Schaper has worked tirelessly these past few weeks developing and implementing our plan to serve over 10,000 meals to students in our area every week. As one of her employees and an employee of the State College School District, making sure our students who need breakfast and lunch in our area has been a challenging and rewarding experience and I can speak for every SCASD food service employee involved in saying we are proud to work for someone with incredible leadership skills in dealing with this important work. Our district was well prepared to handle serving our district students and it is in large part to her hard work and dedication."

Free Meal Order Form Open Now

The form to submit your order for free meals next Wednesday, April 15 is now open. Submit your order here (https://forms.gle/yAesQy3nrXpVapXS9). The deadline to submit your order is Monday at 8 a.m.

Each lunch kit will include five servings for each child of the chosen entree along with bulk portions of vegetables, fruits and milk. Breakfasts will also be provided in the form of five complete meals, one for each child in the household.

Pickups will be on Wednesday from 10 a.m. to 1 p.m. at the State College Area High School North Parking Lot. This lot is located across the street from the main high school building at 653 Westerly Parkway in State College. Upon arrival, families are asked to enter the parking lot via Plaza Drive. Food service staff will then guide you through the process. Children must be present in order for meals to be provided.

If you have no way to pick up your own meals, please fill out this form (https://www.scasd.org/Page/37976) and someone will be in contact with you.

post_text:
Congratulations to the State High Quiz Bowl team on finishing 11th at their national competition.

With tournaments cancelled because of the COVID-19 pandemic, the annually strong team recently switched to virtual competition, concluding its regular season in the WAIT Online Knowledge Event. Against a national field, members Jupiter Ding, Allen Farabaugh, Kyle Hynes, Ananya Tadigadapa and Albert Zhang just missed a top 10 performance, finishing 11th.

Along the way, the quintet beat five teams ranked in the top 100 of high schools, including Adlai Stevenson High School from New York City and East Chapel Hill High School from Chapel Hill, N.C., both of which are ranked higher nationally than the top-ranked Pennsylvania high school, Manheim Township.

Zhang’s individual score placed him in the top 10 among competitors, while Ding and Farabaugh finished with top 50 scores.

post_text:
Athletic Facilities and Playgrounds are Closed

Dear SCASD Community:

While we are under Governor Wolf’s stay-at-home order until April 30, we want to clarify the use of district facilities. To be clear, all playgrounds, tennis courts, and athletic stadiums are closed until further notice.

Because exercise and walking outside are allowed under the order, we support the community’s use of our grounds for exercise and fresh air, as long as you practice social distancing and do not use the playground equipment. However, group activities and any type of congregation are not permitted.

Both our police departments and school district request your assistance to share and support this closure for the well-being of our community. The police and our district administrators are working together to comply with the governor’s order.

We realize this may be an inconvenience, but we all need to have a hand in keeping our community safe and slowing the spread of COVID-19.

Thank you for your cooperation.

Bob O’Donnell
Superintendent of Schools

post_text:
A State College Area High School junior has struck gold with his art.

Wenjun Leng recently received a 2020 Scholastic Art & Writing National Gold Key award for his painting, “Disillusioned,” one of 2,900 artistic and literary works earning national acclaim.

This year, students in grades 7-12 submitted approximately 320,000 works in 29 categories to the long-running, prestigious program. National award winners were selected from 18,000 works that qualified with regional Gold Keys.

"I was really surprised and excited when I found out that I had won a Scholastic Art National Gold award,” said Leng, who studies with AP Studio teacher Maure Irwin-Furmanek. “I want to use this moment to say thank you to my friends, family and teachers who have all pushed and encouraged me to always do my absolute best. Thank you all for having faith in me and always being there to provide feedback."

post_text:
MyOn Reader for Digital Books

Dear K-5 Families,

All SCASD students and teachers in grades K-5 now have access to MyOn Reader. This platform offers a personalized literacy environment that engages students at all reading levels by providing a large library of digital books. Specifically, it walks children through a series of questions and then customizes books to their preferences and reading levels.

Parents interested in MyOn Reader can join one of several webinars to learn how to navigate this tool. Multiple 60-minute training options have been scheduled via Zoom in an attempt to accommodate varying schedules.

Training dates and times for families are as follows:
Wednesday, April 1 - 11 a.m., 2 p.m. or 5:30 p.m.
Thursday, April 2 - 5:30 p.m.
Tuesday, April 7 - 5:30 p.m.
Wednesday, April 9 - 10 a.m, 3:15 p.m., or 5:30 p.m.
Thursday, April 9 - 5:30 p.m.

For more information about MyOn, additional support, and Zoom links for the webinars, please click here: https://sites.google.com/scasd.org/scasdremotelearningsiteforfami/learning-tools

post_text:
Computer and Internet Needs

As we begin our optional remote learning plan this week, we’re still trying to identify students who need a computer and/or Internet access at home. We are prepared to provide a

Chromebook to any students, as well as support to families with Internet access issues. If your child already has a computer at home (laptop, Chromebook, tablet, iPad), that will work with our plan and you do not need to sign up.

Please fill out this form (https://bit.ly/2WFbuxJ) if you require a device at home or lack Internet access. Once your need is identified through the form, we will contact you directly to fulfill your request. Note: This is a new form. If you have previously filled out a form but still need help, please fill it out again. We need to do this because we want to ensure we are connecting with everyone.

If you have any questions, please contact your building principal.

Bob O’Donnell
Superintendent of Schools

post_text:
SCASD Continues to Distribute Meals

We have received word from the PA Dept. of Education that we are able to continue distributing meals under the guidelines of Governor Wolf’s order given last night.

Therefore, for the foreseeable future, meals are being provided every weekday (including today) for all children under the age of 18 while schools are closed. This will continue next week, March 23-27. A breakfast and lunch will be available on a first come, first served basis. Children must be present in order for meals to be provided at the following drive-thru locations:

State College Area High School bus loop from 11 a.m.-12:30 p.m.
Weis Market parking lot on North Atherton Street from 11 a.m.-noon
Ashworth Woods Apartments in Boalsburg from 11:30 a.m.-12:30 p.m.

If you have any questions, please email Food Services Director Megan Schaper at mas15@scasd.org or call 814-231-5093.

Sincerely,

Bob O’Donnell
Superintendent of Schools

This week, we are working with faculty to prepare our remote learning plan scheduled for next week. However, for the plan to work, we need your cooperation.

Specifically, every student needs access to a computer. Therefore, we are assessing the need for Chromebooks among our elementary students. Additionally, we know some of our secondary students might have left their Chromebooks in school prior to spring break.

We are prepared to provide a Chromebook to any student who needs one. However, keep in mind that any computer will work (laptop, Chromebook, tablet, iPad) with the remote learning plan we are developing.

If you need a device at home, please fill out this form. Once your need is identified through the form, we will contact you directly to get you a Chromebook. Click here for the form link: https://forms.gle/wb6FHr31qKsxiefi9

post_text:
Governor Wolf Announces School Closure

Dear Parents and Guardians:

Today, Gov. Tom Wolf announced that all K-12 Pennsylvania schools will be closed for two weeks, effective Monday, March 16. This changes our original plan to make week-to-week decisions on our school closure. While schools will now be closed until March 30, we are still working on a remote learning plan that could begin the week of March 23.

We will be in touch as we assess this new information and our plans come together.

Have a good weekend,

Bob O’Donnell
Superintendent of Schools

post_text:
As most of you are seeing outside, we are experiencing an unusual weather situation today. Typically, we don’t have a snow event specifically during school hours.

Given this, we want you to know that we have been monitoring the weather closely this morning. What we’re currently seeing is that the precipitation will stop in the early afternoon, allowing us to dismiss safely at our regular times and continue evening activities as normal. At this time, we will not be dismissing early.

We will continue watching the conditions and if our plan changes, we will communicate with you as soon as possible.
text:
As most of you are seeing outside, we are experiencing an unusual weather situation today. Typically, we don’t have a snow event specifically during school hours.

Given this, we want you to know that we have been monitoring the weather closely this morning. What we’re currently seeing is that the precipitation will stop in the early afternoon, allowing us to dismiss safely at our regular times and continue evening activities as normal. At this time, we will not be dismissing early.

We will continue watching the conditions and if our plan changes, we will communicate with you as soon as possible.

post_text: Congratulations to State High Alum Esther Seeland on winning the the NCAA ELITE 90 Award. Esther is attending Messiah College where her soccer team just won the NCAA Division III National Championship. ELITE 90 is an award founded by the NCAA which recognizes the true essence of the student-athlete by honoring the individual who has reached the pinnacle of competition at the national championship level in his or her sport, while also achieving the highest academic standard among his or her peers. The Elite 90 is presented to the student-athlete with the highest cumulative grade-point average participating at the finals site for each of the NCAA’s 90 championships.

post_text: On Nov. 19, representatives from the PA. Department of Education Bureau of Special Education were treated to a day-long visit with our students, faculty and staff. The people on the tour visited LifeLink PSU, high school special education classrooms (AS, LSS, MDS, LS, ES), the OVR Transition class, and then enjoyed a delicious lunch made by the students from Judy Brooks and Claire Purcival’s Autistic Support classrooms. Lydia Everhart, transition coordinator, joined the group while visiting the Panorama Village Administrative Center Ellison die cut work site in the Print Shop. The last stop was a visit the LifeLink PSU Apartment. Thank you for coming, we are always proud to showcase our Special Education program!

post_text: Happy Veterans Day from the State College Area School District. Thank you, veterans, and everyone who honored them in our schools today through so many wonderful events and tributes.
text: Happy Veterans Day from the State College Area School District. Thank you, veterans, and everyone who honored them in our schools today through so many wonderful events and tributes.

post_text:
Radio Park Elementary and schools across State College Area School District did their part on Veterans Day to honor veterans and their service to our country.

An assembly at Spring Creek Elementary featured 13 veterans discussing their service and four students reading the Ralph Waldo Emerson poem “A Nation’s Strength.” World War II veteran David Felix was the guest speaker at Corl Street Elementary’s assembly, which included a student orchestra performing a medley of military anthems. Park Forest Elementary held a Veterans Day musical performance in the evening.

Throughout the day, students at Radio Park and Mount Nittany elementary schools, as well as Mount Nittany Middle School, engaged in various classroom lessons and activities centered on thanking veterans and appreciating military service. Radio Park’s activities included parents who are veterans visiting second and third grade classes.

post_text: Congratulations to the girls’ cross country team. Second place at States!
shared_text:
Rebecca Donaghue is with Julie Scott Kwasnica and 11 others.
November 3, 2019 at 3:46 AM ·

2nd PLACE AT PIAA-AAA STATE CHAMPIONSHIPS!!!🏆
What a show they gave us today! Couldn’t be prouder of these ladies. They’ve had the goal of being on the podium since last year when they took 3rd.
Over a sloppy course, they worked together and got it done. First through 1 mile, 3rd at 2 miles, and closed hard to finish in 2nd. State High’s best finish in 25 years!
Huge congrats to the girls who raced today and the entire team who all played an important role in this final outcome. And huge congrats to my amazing assistants, Susan Marshall and Artie Gilkes, our incredible booster club, and all the parents for their support throughout the season.
Go SCXC!!🌟❤️🌟🥈🏆
